      "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body": "> When two transactions in a compact block share the same 6-byte short ID,\r\n\r\nFor an honest peer (ie one constructing the shortids via a random nonce and hash against a valid block that doesn't contain the same transaction twice) the odds of this occurring for a block with under 8k transactions (ie any reasonable block) is about 1-in-8.8million, ie about once in 167 years. I think it probably makes more sense to treat a duplicate shortid as \"this compact block is probably broken/dishonest, so don't even waste CPU scanning the mempool\".",
